\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The classic game theoretical assumptions of players being both rational
 and capable of perfect reasoning has often been criticized.
 People have been shown to often diverge from rational behavior and being
 incapable of applying perfect reasoning (as detailed in Verbrugge 2009).
 Experiments testing how well people apply higher order social reasoning
 also tests these premises to an extend.
 However there are a few problems facing such experiments, which I will
 detail below.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset

The first is mentioned above.
 There might be a discrepancy between the mental resources and capabilities
 of people and how well these resources are drawn upon in actual use.
 In other words, we might want to be careful about whether people do not
 show possession of a Theory of Mind because they do not have it, or because
 it is just not being drawn upon.
 There is possibly a discrepancy between reasoning behind spontaneous and
 reflective tasks (see Keysar et al.
 2003).
 This leads to a related second problem, that application of Theory of Mind
 might be task dependent.
 As (Verbrugge et al.
 2008) writes, in order for a person to apply an appropriate order of Theory
 of Mind, it is necessary that the person recognizes that it is advantageous
 to incorporate this type of knowledge into her decisions.
 This hints that the ability to apply Theory of Mind might not transfer
 from one domain to another, before a person becomes aware that such reasoning
 benefits decision making.
 So, experimental setup might be influence results in related experiments.
 Thirdly, even if players are presumably rational, they cannot be expected
 to make rational plays if rationality of players is not common knowledge.
 That is, if a player does not believe that another player has a Theory
 of Mind, the first player would only model their mental state as such,
 which means the first player intentionally restricting herself to a first-order
 theory of mind.
